03805nam a22005655i 9780226006833DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260068337 a10.7208/97802260068332doi  a(DE-B1597)524002  a(OCoLC)304436367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPR2825b.A36 2008 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a822.3/3a822.331 aAdelman, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlood Relations :bChristian and Jew in The Merchant of Venice /cJanet Adelman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Texts -- t1. Introduction: Strangers within Christianity -- t2. Leaving the Jew’s House: Father, Son, and Elder Brother -- t3. Her Father’s Blood: Conversion, Race, and Nation -- t4. Incising Antonio: The Jew Within -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Blood Relations, Janet Adelman confronts her resistance to The Merchant of Venice as both a critic and a Jew. With her distinctive psychological acumen, she argues that Shakespeare’s play frames the uneasy relationship between Christian and Jew specifically in familial terms in order to recapitulate the vexed familial relationship between Christianity and Judaism. Adelman locates the promise—or threat—of Jewish conversion as a particular site of tension in the play. Drawing on a variety of cultural materials, she demonstrates that, despite the triumph of its Christians, The Merchant of Venice reflects Christian anxiety and guilt about its simultaneous dependence on and disavowal of Judaism. In this startling psycho-theological analysis, both the insistence that Shylock’s daughter Jessica remain racially bound to her father after her conversion and the depiction of Shylock as a bloody-minded monster are understood as antidotes to Christian uneasiness about a Judaism it can neither own nor disown. In taking seriously the religious discourse of The Merchant of Venice, Adelman offers in Blood Relations an indispensable book on the play and on the fascinating question of Jews and Judaism in Renaissance England and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAntisemitism in literature. 0aChristians in literature. 0aJews in literature. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aReligion in literature. 0aShylock (Fictitious character). 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226006833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226006833.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles